What’s the difference between #rstats and @stata? #rstats is open source. BUT here’s the real difference. I don’t trust results from an estimator in #rstats until I have reproduced the same with @stata.

Initially, it might feel that way. But soon one realizes that one is at the mercy of 1000s of package contributors who may or may not support, update or maintain their packages. I had to abandon #rstats for a grad course when some key packages I taught were temporarily abandoned. https://t.co/rKk7qrnyXm

Imagine completing the draft of a book with #rstats (R) & then realize that the packages you demonstrated in the book are no longer available on CRAN. That’s the difference for me. R has to find away to improve documentation & consistency. Orphaned packages are a huge limitation. https://t.co/iWYuP8wJjA

@Stata has been proactive in absorbing the user written packages in the official version. Base R (#rstats) is quite slow, at times reluctant, to do the same. Most charts drawn in R today use #ggplot2 or other user-written tools that should be absorbed in base R for consistency https://t.co/iWYuP8wJjA

@stata excels in richness & comprehensiveness of econometric methods, unparalleled support for marginal analysis with almost all estimators, & documentation in English that one can follow + examples one can replicate. #rstats documentation is not for the faint-hearted. https://t.co/rKk7qrnyXm
What IDE you use for #rstats?

R should follow the lead of dictionaries that are quite conservative but not reluctant to accommodate the evolving vernacular. Developing R in an echo chamber, or acting as strict gatekeepers dictating what’s included or otherwise will limit #RStats’ horizons https://t.co/rxmzdP2BZM

It talks about if we convert #RStats from lazily evaluated to eager evaluation we save memory and time by not creating unnecessary promises object... And can use annotation to explicitly tell #RStats compiler where are we substituting values at run time.

This simple changes speeds up #RStats by almost 2x and it saves 91-96% by not creating promises... Effects memory too..
